# Intuition:
The problem is to add two binary numbers represented as strings, i.e., "101" + "110" should give "1011". We can start by aligning the two binary numbers by adding leading zeros to the shorter string so that both strings have equal lengths. Then we can add the digits from right to left and keep track of any carry generated. Finally, we add the carry to the leftmost position if any.

# Approach:
1. Calculate the lengths of the two input strings.
2. If the length of string a is greater than that of string b, add leading zeros to string b to make its length equal to that of string a. Otherwise, add leading zeros to string a to make its length equal to that of string b.
3. Initialize carry to 0 and an empty string ans.
4. Traverse the two input strings from right to left, one character at a time.
5. For each character, add its value with the corresponding character from the other string and the carry.
6. Determine the value of the current bit and the carry generated.
7. Add the current bit to the left end of the ans string.
8. Finally, if there is any carry left, add it to the leftmost position of the ans string.
9. Return the ans string.

# Complexity:
- Time Complexity: The algorithm has a time complexity of O(N), where N is the length of the longer input string. This is because we traverse the input strings once from right to left, which takes O(N) time. 
- Space Complexity: The algorithm has a space complexity of O(N), where N is the length of the longer input string. This is because we store the result in an ans string which can have a maximum length of N+1.

