# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- We have to find the `sum` so we need to start from the **right** end of both the numbers.
- To start iterating from the right end of the strings we first calculated the last indices `indexA` & `indexB`
- To store the digits sum we initialized `digitSum=0`
- To store the carry we initialized `carry=0`
- Then we keep a check if `a` & `b` is non-Empty if yes we increase the `digitSum`
- To keep check of the `carry`, we check if `digitSum > 1`. If yes, that means there is a `carry` and it needs to be considered.

- At last, we insert the calculated digit at the start of the StringBuilder.
- And then return the sum after converting it to String via `toString()`. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: `O(n)`
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: `O(1)`
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Please give this an UPVOTE if you find it useful!

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public String addBinary(String a, String b) {
        StringBuilder sum= new StringBuilder("");
        int indexA= a.length()-1;
        int indexB =b.length()-1;
        int carry=0;
        int digitSum=0;
        while(indexA >= 0 || indexB >= 0 || carry > 0 ){
            digitSum = carry;
            if(indexA >= 0) digitSum += a.charAt(indexA--)-'0';
            if(indexB >= 0) digitSum += b.charAt(indexB--)-'0';
            if(digitSum >1) carry=1;
            else carry=0;
            sum.insert(0, digitSum%2);
        }
        return sum.toString();
    }
}
